<article style="padding: 15px" class="post-4493 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail category-general category-pet-blog tag-apparel tag-clothing tag-coat tag-dog tag-dog-blanket tag-dogs tag-fall tag-rug tag-sweater tag-winter entry" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/CreativeWork">
    <header class="entry-header">
        <h1 class="entry-title" itemprop="headline">The Perfect Guide to Fall and Winter Dog Clothing</h1>
        <p class="entry-meta"><time class="entry-time" itemprop="datePublished" datetime="2016-10-21T08:44:16-05:00">October 21, 2016</time> By <span class="entry-author" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person"><a href="https://blog.jefferspet.com/author/mloman/" class="entry-author-link" itemprop="url" rel="author"><span class="entry-author-name" itemprop="name">Maressa Loman</span></a></span> </p>
    </header>
    <div class="entry-content" itemprop="text">
        <p>For many dogs, clothing is a necessary and essential part of staying warm during the colder months. Some dogs are unable to maintain the body heat necessary to keep warm and may require additional protection in fall and winter. While fur can be insulating, not all fur (or dogs) are created equal. If you&#8217;re unsure whether or not your dog needs additional layering, look at their behavior. Two common signs your dog needs clothing include shivering and a reluctance to go outdoors.</p>
        <p>Overwhelmed by all the choices? Jeffers Pet is here to help. From measuring for size to breaking down key features, this all-inclusive guide will help you select the best dog clothing for your canine companion.</p>
        <h2>Dog Sweaters</h2>
        <figure id="attachment_6610" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-6610" style="width: 311px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="#nothing" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-6610" src="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/RR1DA.1-244x300.jpg" alt="A medium-sized dog wearing a red dog sweater that features stars. " width="311" height="382" srcset="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/RR1DA.1-244x300.jpg 244w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/RR1DA.1-768x944.jpg 768w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/RR1DA.1-833x1024.jpg 833w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/RR1DA.1.jpg 1302w" sizes="(max-width: 311px) 100vw, 311px" /></a>
            <figcaption id="caption-attachment-6610" class="wp-caption-text"></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>Dogs with thin or sparse fur may struggle in colder environments. Even the fall weather may make your pup shiver. Even fluffy dogs like the Shih Tzu and the Pomeranian may need extra warmth due to not having a thick undercoat. A <a href="https://www.jefferspet.com/categories/dog/supplies/clothing-accessories/dog-coats-sweaters?product_type%5B%5D=Sweater" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">sweater</a> is perfect for keeping your pup warm indoors and outdoors.</p>
        <p>Sweaters are an excellent choice for breeds with short legs and longer bodies such as Corgis and Dachshunds. When selecting clothing for these types of dogs, make considerations for their weight and the type of material. A smaller sweater has more stretch and &#8220;give&#8221; than a dog coat that&#8217;s too small. Sweaters are also less likely to drag on the ground than coats.</p>
        <h2><strong>Measuring for Dog Clothing<br />
            </strong></h2>
        <figure id="attachment_4502" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-4502" style="width: 551px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-4502" src="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Size.png" alt="Measuring for Dog Clothing" width="551" height="381" srcset="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Size.png 800w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Size-300x207.png 300w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Size-768x531.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 551px) 100vw, 551px" />
            <figcaption id="caption-attachment-4502" class="wp-caption-text">Measuring for Dog Clothing</figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>It&#8217;s important to ensure your dog&#8217;s sweater is properly fitted. Measure your dog from the base of the neck to the base of the tail when sizing most pet apparel.<b> </b>Make sure the sweater isn&#8217;t too tight or too low to the ground but leaves just enough room for your dog to have range of motion.</p>
        <h3><strong>Fabrics</strong></h3>
        <figure id="attachment_7301" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-7301" style="width: 430px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="#nothing" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-7301" src="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Nordic-Knit-Dog-Sweater-277x300.jpg" alt="A medium-sized poddle wearing a Christmas themed gray and teal Nordic Knit Dog Sweater that features bones." width="430" height="465" srcset="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Nordic-Knit-Dog-Sweater-277x300.jpg 277w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Nordic-Knit-Dog-Sweater.jpg 670w" sizes="(max-width: 430px) 100vw, 430px" /></a>
            <figcaption id="caption-attachment-7301" class="wp-caption-text"><strong><a href="#nothing" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Nordic Knit Dog Sweater</a></strong></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>The material of the sweater determines how much heat is insulated to keep your pup warm. Wool is considered to be a great insulator but can irritate the skin, while knit fabric allows air to flow and is stretchy. However, don&#8217;t shy away from a great wool sweater! <a href="http://www.petmd.com/dog/seasonal/evr_dg_sweaters_for_dogs" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">PetMD </a>recommends a good blend of washable wool and cotton or acrylic will work just fine.</p>
        <h2>Dog Coats or Rugs</h2>
        <figure id="attachment_6612" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-6612" style="width: 451px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="#nothing" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-6612" src="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/JEFAWL.0-300x281.jpg" alt="A doberman wearing a vibrant sunset serape print dog rug. " width="451" height="422" srcset="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/JEFAWL.0-300x281.jpg 300w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/JEFAWL.0-768x720.jpg 768w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/JEFAWL.0-1024x960.jpg 1024w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/JEFAWL.0.jpg 2048w" sizes="(max-width: 451px) 100vw, 451px" /></a>
            <figcaption id="caption-attachment-6612" class="wp-caption-text"><strong><a href="#nothing" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Jeffers Expression Sunset Serape Dog Rug</a></strong></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>Many different terms are used to describe winter <a href="#nothing" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">dog coats</a> and <a href="#nothing" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">dog blankets</a>. Whether you call it a <a href="#nothing" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">dog rug</a>, coat, or blanket, the most important question to ask is if the product will keep your dog warm and protected.</p>
        <h2>Dog Coats and Rugs Features</h2>
        <h3>Denier</h3>
        <figure id="attachment_6613" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-6613" style="width: 493px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="#nothing" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-6613" src="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/FO1LG.0-300x224.jpg" alt="A small dog wearing a red Rambo Duo Dog Blanket made of denier fabric. " width="493" height="368" srcset="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/FO1LG.0-300x224.jpg 300w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/FO1LG.0-768x574.jpg 768w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/FO1LG.0-1024x765.jpg 1024w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/FO1LG.0.jpg 1612w" sizes="(max-width: 493px) 100vw, 493px" /></a>
            <figcaption id="caption-attachment-6613" class="wp-caption-text"><strong><a  target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Rambo Duo Dog Blanket</a></strong></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>Denier refers to the tightness of the thread in the material. Normally the higher the count, the more resistant it is to tears. A higher denier will normally withstand a lot more romping and stomping, so your dog’s coat should last a few more seasons.</p>
        <h3>Gram Fill</h3>
        <figure id="attachment_6614" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-6614" style="width: 521px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://www.jefferspet.com/products/jeffers-solaris-dog-rug-sapphire-plaid" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-6614" title="Dog Clothing" src="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/JEFAN1.0.Emerald-Plaid-300x253.jpg" alt="A small dog wearing an emerald plaid dog rug from Jeffers made with gram fill fabric. " width="521" height="439" srcset="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/JEFAN1.0.Emerald-Plaid-300x253.jpg 300w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/JEFAN1.0.Emerald-Plaid-768x648.jpg 768w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/JEFAN1.0.Emerald-Plaid-1024x864.jpg 1024w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/JEFAN1.0.Emerald-Plaid.jpg 1095w" sizes="(max-width: 521px) 100vw, 521px" /></a>
            <figcaption id="caption-attachment-6614" class="wp-caption-text"><strong><a href="#nothong" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Jeffers Solaris Dog Rug in Emerald Plaid</a></strong></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>Gram fill is the next term seen in a dog’s winter coat. This refers to the inner filling and determines the warmth. Most are a poly-fiber fill. The higher the gram count, the warmer your dog’s winter coat will be.</p>
        <h3>Rip-Stop</h3>
        <figure id="attachment_6615" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-6615" style="width: 460px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="https://www.jefferspet.com/products/jeffers-premium-nylon-rip-stop-blanket" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-6615" src="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/MFIA1.0.Orange-Black-300x225.jpg" alt="A French Bulldog wearing an orange and black dog blanket from Jeffers made of ripstop fabric. " width="460" height="345" srcset="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/MFIA1.0.Orange-Black-300x225.jpg 300w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/MFIA1.0.Orange-Black-768x576.jpg 768w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/MFIA1.0.Orange-Black-1024x768.jpg 1024w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/MFIA1.0.Orange-Black.jpg 1600w" sizes="(max-width: 460px) 100vw, 460px" /></a>
            <figcaption id="caption-attachment-6615" class="wp-caption-text"><strong><a href="#nothing" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Jeffers Premium Nylon Ripstop Dog Blanket</a></strong></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>Dog clothing made from Rip-Stop fabric refers to a material that has been reinforced using a special sewing technique. This technique makes clothing resistant to ripping or tearing. It is important to note that rip-stop does not equate to rip-proof.</p>
        <h2>Dog Clothing Add-ons</h2>
        <figure id="attachment_6616" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-6616" style="width: 465px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="#nothing" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-6616" title="Dog Clothing" src="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/FO1LA.0-252x300.jpg" alt="A medium-sized dog with a horse wearing a black and white Rambo Waterproof Dog Blanket." width="465" height="554" srcset="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/FO1LA.0-252x300.jpg 252w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/FO1LA.0-768x914.jpg 768w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/FO1LA.0-861x1024.jpg 861w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/FO1LA.0.jpg 1721w" sizes="(max-width: 465px) 100vw, 465px" /></a>
            <figcaption id="caption-attachment-6616" class="wp-caption-text"><strong><a href="nothing" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Rambo Waterproof Dog Blanket</a></strong></figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>There are nice additional features that can benefit you, your pet, or both! Reflective trim is great for evening walks, and hind leg straps help keep the coat securely in place. A variety of apparel can be secured by a Velcro belly band or by hardware that you loop the band through. If you have a wiggly dog (like most of us!), Velcro makes the fitting process faster and easier.</p>
        <p>Inclement weather a major concern? Look for clothing that is waterproof and/or windproof.</p>
        <figure id="attachment_7302" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-7302" style="width: 460px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><a href="#nothing" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-7302" src="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/WeatherBeeta-Parka-Deluxe-Dog-Coat-1200D-300x300.jpg" alt="A golden retriever wearing a blue WeatherBeeta Parka Deluxe Dog Coat featuring a multi-colored stag print. " width="460" height="460" srcset="https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/WeatherBeeta-Parka-Deluxe-Dog-Coat-1200D-300x300.jpg 300w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/WeatherBeeta-Parka-Deluxe-Dog-Coat-1200D-150x150.jpg 150w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/WeatherBeeta-Parka-Deluxe-Dog-Coat-1200D-100x100.jpg 100w, https://blog.jefferspet.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/WeatherBeeta-Parka-Deluxe-Dog-Coat-1200D.jpg 400w" sizes="(max-width: 460px) 100vw, 460px" /></a>
            <figcaption id="caption-attachment-7302" class="wp-caption-text"><strong><a href="#nothing" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">WeatherBeeta Parka Deluxe Dog Coat</a></strong></figcaption>
        </figure>



